Refugees from 6 Countries
Overview

This project explores 20 years of global refugee data — combining UNHCR displacement records, ACLED conflict events, and World Bank GDP data to understand what actually drives forced migration and where people go when they flee.

Animated Bubble Chart
001
GDP & Displacement
GDP vs Refugees

Countries with lower GDP consistently produce more refugees. Each bubble is a country — watch size and position shift from 2000 to 2024 as conflict and economic collapse drive displacement.

Stacked Bar Chart
002
Continental Trends
Refugees by Continent

Africa leads throughout the entire period. Notice the sharp European spike from 2022 — entirely driven by Ukraine. Asia stays high due to Afghanistan and Myanmar.

Animated Choropleth
003
Geographic View
World Map

A global map of refugee origins, animated year by year. The concentration of displacement in just a handful of countries becomes immediately visible.

Sankey Diagram
004
Origin → Asylum
Migration Flow

Refugees don't move to wealthier countries — they move to nearby ones. Pakistan, Iran, Uganda and Bangladesh absorb far more than Germany or the US combined.

Treemap
005
Flow Breakdown
Origin vs Destination

Each rectangle shows a country pair and its refugee volume. Click to drill into the origin-to-asylum breakdown and see which countries are most interconnected.

Donut Chart
006
Crisis Concentration
Top Origin Countries

Just 6 countries — Afghanistan, South Sudan, Somalia, Sudan, Ukraine, and Myanmar — account for nearly 60% of all refugees produced over the last 20 years.

Donut Chart
007
Who Takes Refugees In
Top Asylum Countries

The top refugee-receiving countries are not the wealthiest. Pakistan, Iran, Uganda and Ethiopia consistently absorb the most — proximity matters more than prosperity.

Animated Bar
008
Africa Deep Dive
Africa by Country

Year-by-year breakdown of African refugee origins. A small cluster of countries — Sudan, Somalia, DRC — dominate the continent's numbers throughout the period.

Animated Bar
009
Asia Deep Dive
Asia by Country

Afghanistan and Myanmar drive the vast majority of Asia's refugee numbers across the full 20-year window, with spikes tied directly to political events.

Animated Bar
010
Europe Deep Dive
Europe by Country

Ukraine's emergence from 2022 is dramatic — it reshapes the European refugee landscape entirely in a single year, dwarfing all previous European displacement.

Animated Bar
011
South America
South America Deep Dive

Venezuela becomes the dominant source from 2018 onward, reflecting the country's political and economic collapse — a crisis largely invisible in global headlines.
